{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517198"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:52:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:52:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12784"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12784"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.08,0.17,0.47,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5223"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77479"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5223"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62991"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44793"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77479"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a two month history of persistent epigastric pain and bloating, worse a few hours after a meal. He thinks he might have lost some weight during this time. His history includes hypertension (on ramipril) and obstructive sleep apnoea (uses CPAP). He takes little exercise and drinks two glasses of wine a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 135/85 mmHg, pulse 86/min, temperature 37.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 12/min. His BMI is 29. His abdomen is soft, non-tender and not distended. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. His haematological and biochemical investigations are all normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Esomeprazole","CT abdomen","Lifestyle advice and review in six months","Endoscopy","Esomeprazole + amoxicillin + clarithromycin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has recent onset of dyspepsia and it is quite possible that he has a peptic ulcer to explain his symptoms. However, he does have an alarm symptom (weight loss). In a patient under 55 years of age, dyspepsia plus one alarm symptom (weight loss, melaena, vomiting, anaemia, dysphagia or a palpable abdominal mass) is an indication for \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopy, \u003C/strong\u003Egiven the concern for either gastric or oesophageal malignancy as the underlying cause of the symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEsomeprazole \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be used to provide empiric treatment for dyspepsia when it is presumed to be secondary to gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD). This can only be assumed in a patient under 55 years of age without any alarm features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELifestyle advice \u003C/strong\u003Eis certainly important for this man, but with the presence of an alarm symptom it would be prudent to get an endoscopy to rule out malignancy. Lifestyle advice might include exercise and avoiding trigger foods, eating smaller, more frequent meals, and avoiding eating late at night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst his abdominal symptoms could have a sinister underlying cause, in the absence of specific symptoms a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to detect anything abnormal. For example, if this patient\u0027s symptoms were due to a gastric cancer, the tumour would not necessarily be of sufficient size to be visible on the scan. If this the the diagnosis that is going through the doctor\u0027s mind, an endoscopic examination of the upper digestive tract would be much more useful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETriple therapy \u003Cstrong\u003E(esomeprazole + amoxicillin + clarithromycin) \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be quite appropriate to prescribe to eradicate an H. pylori infection, but the presence of this organism should be identified first. This can be done at the time of endoscopy or by a urea breath test.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of alarm symptoms in a patient under 55 years of age, demands further investigation.","Endoscopy is the investigation of choice for evaluating upper gastrointestinal symptoms with alarm features."],"references":["Black CJ, Paine PA, Agrawal A, Aziz I, Eugenicos MP, Houghton LA, Hungin P, Overshott R, Vasant DH, Rudd S, Winning RC, Corsetti M, Ford AC. British Society of Gastroenterology guidelines on the management of functional dyspepsia. Gut. 2022 Sep;71(9):1697-1723. doi: 10.1136/gutjnl-2022-327737. Epub 2022 Jul 7. PMID: 35798375; PMCID: PMC9380508 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35798375/","Grimpen F, Pavli P. Rational investigation of upper abdominal pain. Aust Fam Physician. 2008 Aug;37(8):602-7. PMID: 18704205. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18704205/","ASGE Standards of Practice Committee; Shaukat A, Wang A, Acosta RD, Bruining DH, Chandrasekhara V, Chathadi KV, Eloubeidi MA, Fanelli RD, Faulx AL, Fonkalsrud L, Gurudu SR, Kelsey LR, Khashab MA, Kothari S, Lightdale JR, Muthusamy VR, Pasha SF, Saltzman JR, Yang J, Cash BD, DeWitt JM. The role of endoscopy in dyspepsia. Gastrointest Endosc. 2015 Aug;82(2):227-32. doi: 10.1016/j.gie.2015.04.003. Epub 2015 May 29. PMID: 26032200. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26032200/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62991"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12784"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62991"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T09:02:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T09:02:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5223"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77479"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags